sourceQuestion:
For a string w, we define w^R to be the reverse of w. For example, if w = 01101 then w^R = 10110. Which of the following languages is/are context-free?

A. {ww^R | w in {0,1}^*}
B. {ww^R w | w in {0,1}^*}
C. {ww^R | w in {0,1,2}^*}
D. {ww^R w | w in {0,1,2}^*}

parsed.stem:
Consider the following languages:
L_1 = {ww | w in {a,b}^*}
L_2 = {a^m b^n c^n | m >= 1, n >= 0}

Which of the following statements is/are FALSE?

sourceQuestion:
Consider the context-free grammar G below:
  S -> aSb | X
  X -> aX | b
where S and X are non-terminals, and a and b are terminal symbols. The starting non-terminal is S.

Which one of the following statements is CORRECT?
A. The language generated by G is {a^(m+n) b^n | m >= 0, n >= 0}
B. The language generated by G is {a^(n+1) b^n | n >= 0}
C. The language generated by G is {a^n b^(n+1) | n >= 0}
D. The language generated by G is not a regular language

parsed.stem:
Consider the following two languages over the alphabet {a, b, c}, where m and n are natural numbers.
  L1 = {a^m b^n c^(m+n) | m, n >= 1}
  L2 = {a^m b^n c^(mn) | m, n >= 1}

Which ONE of the following statements is CORRECT?

sourceQuestion:
In the context-free grammar below, S is the start symbol, a and b are terminals, and epsilon denotes the empty string.
  S -> aSAb | epsilon
  A -> bA | b

The grammar generates the language
A. {(ab)^n | n >= 0}
B. {a^m b^n | m <= n}
C. {a^n b^(2n) | n >= 0}
D. {a^m b^n | m >= n}

Consider a CFG with the following productions.

S -> AA | B
A -> 0A | A0 | 1
B -> 0B0 | 1

S is the start symbol, A and B are non-terminals and 0 and 1 are the terminals. The language generated by this grammar is:

A. {0^i 1 0^j | i, j >= 0} ∪ {0^n 1 0^n | n >= 0}
B. {0^i 1 0^j | i, j >= 0}
C. {0^n 1 0^n | n >= 0}
D. The set of all strings over {0, 1} containing at least two 1's

Consider the following sets:
S1: Set of all recursively enumerable languages over the alphabet {0, 1}
S2: Set of all syntactically valid C programs
S3: Set of all languages over the alphabet {0, 1}
S4: Set of all non-regular languages over the alphabet {0, 1}
Which of the above sets are uncountable?
A. S1 and S2
B. S3 and S4
C. S2 and S3
D. S1 and S4

